<DOC><DOCNO> AP890511-0219 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0051EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-11 0711</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0744</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   House tax-writers rejected President Bush'ssavings and loan bailout plan, approving an alternative thatthreatens to swell the federal deficit over the next three years by$43 billion to $50 billion and possibly force a veto showdown withthe White House.   The House Ways and Means Committee, with 2 of 13 Republicansjoining its 23 Democrats, voted 25-11 Wednesday to include thegovernment's full $50 billion share of the most massive corporatebailout in history in the fiscal 1989, 1990 and 1991 budgets.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Amway Corp. got its foot in the door of AvonProducts Inc., offering more than $2 billion to buy its larger andmore conservative rival in person-to-person sales.   Analysts predicted the $39-a-share cash offer Wednesday byAmway, known for its sales force's evangelistic attitude, wouldprecipitate a drawn-out battle with Avon, made famous by itsgenteel ``Avon Lady'' image of years past.   Amway in partnership with Minneapolis investor Irwin Jacobs owns10.3 percent of Avon's outstanding common shares, but Jacobs is notparticipating in the purchase offer, Amway said.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Securities and Exchange Commission hasapproved rule changes designed to make the securities industry'sarbitration system more fair to disgruntled customers.   By a 5-0 vote, the commission Wednesday authorized a series ofchanges, spurred by complaints from unhappy investors whodiscovered after the October 1987 stock crash that they had signedaway their right to sue their brokers.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Gary G. Lynch, the driving force behind theinsider trading investigation that rocked Wall Street, said he isleaving the Securities and Exchange Commission after four years asits top cop.   Lynch, a lanky, soft-spoken 38-year-old attorney who became theSEC's youngest-ever enforcement director in early 1985, saidWednesday he will step down in mid-July. He said he had no specificplans after that.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Convicted stock brokerage founder Boyd L.Jefferies testified he engaged in four unlawful stock deals withcorporate takeover strategist Paul A. Bilzerian.   Testifying at Bilzerian's securities fraud trial at federalcourt in Manhattan on Wednesday, Jefferies, who said he only metthe Singer Co. chairman once, detailed their dealings in four stocktransactions in 1985 and 1986.   The indictment alleges that Jefferies secretly held stock forBilzerian in four deals involving Cluett, Peabody andamp; Co., HammerhillPaper Co., H.H. Robertson Co., and Armco Inc.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The federal bankruptcy court extended a biddingdeadline on Eastern Airlines for at least one potential suitor, asa bidder for Eastern's profitable Northeast shuttle raised itsoffer for that business.   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland extended the Wednesdaydeadline for an investor group led by Joseph Ritchie, a prominentChicago commodities trader, to give it more time to receivefinancial information from Eastern.</TEXT><DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Campbell Soup Co. settled a year-old disputewith nine states over advertised claims that the company's soupspromote good health and may help prevent some types of cancer.   Under terms of a court settlement announced Wednesday, thenation's largest soup producer agreed to pay the states $35,000each and to change certain advertising practices. The money will beused by each state for consumer education and aid.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Continental Can Co. developed a secret andsophisticated computer program used nationwide to deny longtimeemployees pension benefits, a federal judge has ruled.   In a sharply worded opinion Wednesday against the company, U.S.District Judge H. Lee Sarokin directed Continental Can to beginnegotiating settlements with about 2,500 Continental workers. Coststo the company could approach $500 million.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices rebounded from an eight-day slide in lacklustertrading Wednesday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose3.12 points to finish at 2,374.45.   The dollar continued a minor retreat, digesting the gains thattook it to nine-month highs at the start of the week. Gold priceswere mixed.   Bond prices edged down.   Prices of frozen pork belly futures soared the permitted dailylimit of 2 cents a pound for the second straight day. Otherlivestock and meat futures finished mixed; energy futures werewidely mixed; precious metals were lower; and grains and soybeanswere mixed.</TEXT></DOC>